column1: Will Lebanon's parliament, the Chamber of Deputies, elect a new President of the Republic before 1 January 2023?

column6: I don't see this being resolved in Dec 2022. Some further info here: https://www.thenationalnews.com/mena/lebanon/2022/11/17/lebanons-parliament-fails-for-sixth-time-to-elect-president/
they are doing it right now the UN is there with interested NATO members the UN will validate the results in about for days I learned this on c-span 2
One month left, and no positive movement. Worse, this article quotes Hezbollah's leader saying they're in no rush:

They're still debating, dropping to 1%https://www.thenationalnews.com/mena/lebanon/2022/11/17/lebanons-parliament-fails-for-sixth-time-to-elect-president/"The Lebanese Parliament on Thursday failed for a sixth time to elect the country’s next president as government vacuum rumbles on.Blank votes again received the highest count, with 46, while independent MP Michel Moawad received 43. Parliament Speaker, Nabih Berri, set the seventh presidential session for next Thursday.Two thirds of the vote in the 128-seat parliament is needed for a candidate to win in the first round, with an absolute majority required in subsequent rounds.It was the second parliamentary session since the term of former president Michel Aoun ended in late October. It took 46 sessions, two and a half years and a series of political deals behind closed doors for Mr Aoun to be elected in 2016.
Looking at the historical election speed in Lebanon, its almost "no" due to the limited time remaining and the participation within election would be limited due to the seasonal holidays.
Another attempt at electing a president ends in nothing: https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_Lebanese_presidential_election

I don't think they will agree due to different groups that interfere with government roles and some who have power. Besides, the weak current government parties and minimum collaboration from the Lebanese leaders and crises will even make it longer.

The various parties in the Lebanese govt have a history of NOT being able to agree. This office is very symbolic and very important. So, BECAUSE it's important for them to pick one, they're going to take a LONG time to pick one.

As @kevins has shown, these sorts of power vacuums are common historically in Lebanon, and there have been seemingly insurmountable issues with getting the rival political factions to agree on a consensus candidate. The time is definitely short.
This is the first time I’ve looked into Lebanon in any capacity so please do correct any errors I’ve made.
Last time it took 29 months to elect a new president.
